en: Harvard 1959.188
beazley_number
collection_history
Gift of Frederick M. Watkins
comparanda

The style is very close to that of the Pig Painter and he may well be the artist; cf. the komos scenes on the column-krater Harvard 1960.346 (ARV2, 563, 8). The shape and ornament also find good parallels on vases decorated by the Pig Painter; e.g. Munich 2346 (ARV2, 565, 32 bis). For the shape particularly, cf. a pelike in Gela, formerly in the Navarra-Jacona collection (ARV2, 565, 32).
condit

Broken and repaired, with several fragments restored in plaster. No repainting. All the heads are preserved. A large fragment missing from the center of Side A includes much of the woman's body and parts of the column-krater and stool. On Side B, parts of all three figures are missing, with nearly all of the man at left gone.

shape_description

Becker 1977, 97, assigns it to her "Mannerist Class with Early Classical Connections," along with pelikai by other early Mannerist painters such as the Agrigento and Leningrad Painters. Among the characteristics of the Class are the narrow upper body, tall neck, and torus foot.
